Higgs Boson Decorated
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole stir last summer, and for cause.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, nothing like that.
And then it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is good for the Higgs.
We know without a doubt that we are holding an authentic new particle, and that it looks a lot like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data revealed this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm it, but there is still a lack of data to be perfectly certain of it.
Let us suppose, however, that it is the Higgs, since the chances of being deceived seem thin, and let us see what this is all about.
There is, in this low world, a fatally indisputable law wanting that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
But even if particle physics is a strange world, it turns out that it also has such a law: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting largely of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify the particles into two categories.
In a corner there are good citizens named farmers, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And in the other there are bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - in any case, not for this principle, which means that they can well be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons then divide themselves into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, indeed) The Part Adventure, Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not approach here, and the "particules of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all beasts as exotic as we might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of an extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" that is the "message" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "distorts" the electromagnetic field in this precise place, somewhat like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbing" there is an electromagnetic wave (of light, or of infrared, or of ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing other than a photon - and therefore, one of the bosons "bearers of force".
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, to the difference that it's another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
However, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, which only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why we need a huge particle accelerator like CERN's - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27km ring of circumference! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is useful again to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is not all particles, nor all materials, that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like the magnets, do, but others don't - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold himself on a fridge.
And in the same way, not all the particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like photon, yours) don't have one.
Now, what can "bring" all these researches, ask Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any differences between the observations and predictions of the MS.
In fact, there are several who have a strong desire to find it, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and plug some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, proposing no explanation for gravity (ops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-ops!).
But no such deviations have been found at CERN until now.
Impact
The impact of this research on the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. All-World, they are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be no such research.
Keep in mind: at the very beginning of the 1960s, laser pioneers in the Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution that their work would trigger.
They were talking about scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 -, initially the laser was seen as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the search.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a small light sensor during his optical work in 1969.
This sensor, although not at all its original intention, now serves as a "eye" for all digital cameras in the world, and has earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that we really never know...
