"I no longer have wishes in life," she says, before accepting a mask for her to help her breathe.
However, in the next few days, she awaits a final visit of her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, with a group of volunteers, we provide body care and food aid.
It's palliative care, given when there's nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when we know we all end up dying someday.
Here, life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the house.
Whether it's physical, emotional, or spiritual comfort.
By dying, we will agree to give mouth care to brandy or Pepsi, as requested.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died during the night.
