At Victor-Gadbois' house, the days follow but don't look like each other.
Along with an old 93-year-old man who enjoys his last family assembly in the courtyard, well-done in his pillows while he is in his honour, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and two young children, after having tried everything to survive.
"For six months, there have always been three to five beds that are occupied by cancer patients under 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois house come from their homes, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e., care designed to ease suffering when a patient has reached the terminal stage of his life, whether at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Grand Montréal Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec health care that causes several physicians specializing in palliative care to fear the adoption of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by summits of palliative care including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not effective enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in emergency, in great pain, without doing the necessary to relieve her.
I fear that patients will only ask to die because they do not receive adequate care.
And at the same time, several oncologists hang on their patients until the last day, despite the worst predictions.
Helen Richard's survival hopes were already minimal when she abandoned a proven chemotherapy.
When I announced to my oncologist that I was stopping the treatment, she told me that she regretted I was stopping fighting, she told me.
But she told me I was done!
Not all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the sick people who are asking to die thank the caregivers for not accessing their application after they have been relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Grand Montréal Palliative Care Society, patients would be refractory to pain treatment in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, physicians often resort to palliative sedation, which returns to sleep the patient until the time of death, sporadic or permanent.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of the suffering.
Increasingly, the unsatisfied patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But it doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to euthanize me," it means "I want to be relieved."
