Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as a 20th member of this agency, the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the years that followed it has participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, Poland's road to outer space began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always meet understanding.
For example, I would like to refer to A. Šternfeld's conference at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on December 6, 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled " Introduction to Astronautics ".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Award in France for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote numerous books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a spreader of world-renowned astronauts, his contribution has been rewarded by the fact that his name has been given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.
As early as 1925 a drain was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocketed engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
Nor is it clear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the drain.
The only known information on this drain is that of the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to the rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the records that this research had reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, research has been interrupted.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" of a author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both of these projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all rocket technology projects were conducted by the interim scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, further work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to Polish astronomical society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is a company in the November 1954 issue of the issue of the issue, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Subowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to Astronautics
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research was of the future.
In early 1956, the Polish astronomical society (PTA) made efforts to enter the international astronomical federation (created in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first President of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956 onwards, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the Meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This 1,800-metre rocket was 80 cm long and weighed slightly less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, RM-1A, was built and, during the summer of 1959, two-storey RM-2 rocket flight tests were started in the Bledov desert.
This rocket was 1.4 metres long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have ranged up to 14.5 km and served to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, followed by the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 litre, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 litre and in Meteor-1C it was 0.62 litre.
The maximum range of all these types of equipment was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
The entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a COSPAR national committee two years later should be mentioned.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
