In November 1979, a crowd of protesters from Islamist students attacked the US Embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had been supporting his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer the U.S. administration a positive outcome; it could not, indeed, abandon Shah, because it would have severely shaken the trust of its allies in other countries.
