Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany chose to abstain during the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must exercise caution, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but was not too critical of Israel.
At the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen to abstain during the vote on the establishment of an area of air exclusion.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany having difficulty adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore face several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that they are still stunning to find this role, but they are on the path of a "more normal" foreign policy.
External policy, such as in France or Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including national dossiers.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China and the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the conflict in the Middle East and the abstention in the vote of the United Nations?
First, Germany has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to clash with public opinion, but also with the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive element.
However, I would not give too much importance to this because it is not a purely unilateral relationship.
But this is, in any case, a key element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany have a negative impact on its relations with the United States by choosing to abstain in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I believe that the Europeans and the Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think that the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has shown that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, views on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States has announced their veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great that they always seem to be.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from overcrowding with Netanyahou's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of major European partners, on the other?
I don't think it makes things easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore be included in a broader policy line and must assert their unique position.
That is what they are currently doing in the euro issue.
In my opinion, Germany will in the future take on a role as a locomotive and push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
In my view, however, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that further marks their independence.
Does Germany see itself as a major player on the international stage, and does Germany just want to play a key role?
Or is it still difficult to assume leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still has difficulties playing a more important role.
If we look at, for example, the euro crisis, we notice that whenever Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things easier for the Germans.
In fact, this is still the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It has to deal with neighbours and very varied opinions, and this is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy only diminishes, but at the moment, the EU does not fill this gap, so who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant for them and if they're only less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyze the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
