Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and blennorrhea (or gonorrhea).
Common STIs are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Pubis powders and gala belong to parasitic STIs.
Which groups are mainly concerned?
Syphilis and blennorrhage often occur in men who have sexual relations with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute considers that sexual contact between men causes at least four out of five syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia, trichomonase, candidiasis (fungic), blennorrhage and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of spread of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, some 20% of new HIV infections are observed in this group.
In young people, there is a significantly higher incidence of chlamydia-related infections than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections concern young people aged 15-25.
In addition, in Germany, the human papilloma virus is common among young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Institut Robert-Koch, the number of cases of syphilis has more than doubled in 10 years: the number has increased from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has decreased.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one-tenth from the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause abscess in genital organs, urinary pain, white loss, low-ventral pain, and the appearance of buttons and warts.
However, they do not regularly cause any pain or other symptom and therefore remain hidden.
How to protect yourself?
Condoms may reduce the risk of infection, but do not protect 100%.
The reason is that pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted by lubricating infection or by close body contacts.
The experts therefore recommend that any person who frequently changes from sexual partners regularly undergo examinations.
Most rapidly detected ISTs can be cured and late sequelae can be avoided.
