Prosecutors tried to demonstrate, on Friday, that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of being the source of the biggest leak of confidential information in the entire history of the American army -- missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claimed to have suffered during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits to Manning by officers during their nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a motion demanding that the Manning case be classified on the grounds that the kidnapping was under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- occurred one day after Manning testified that he wanted to commit suicide during his detention.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then posted online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was their source.
During the Friday hearing, Fein examined with Manning the forms that the officers had completed after their meeting with Manning during his detention at the military prison in Quantico, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment he was given to him was "excellent" and that the treatment he had had in prison was generally "very professional."
The forms did not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed oral concerns about certain problems and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would address them, but did not record the issues raised.
"They wrote "no problems" (after addressing concerns), and yet this did not mean that I had not raised any problems," Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to change his restrictive status as a "risk of injury".
The military stated that they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for the risk of suicide -- for his protection and safety of others.
"I wanted staff to know that I was going well, and I wanted people to withdraw this status... in order to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the base of the Marine Corps in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He stated that he had considered suicide when he was in Kuwait and had fainted once because of heat.
