"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon at this cage," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning stated that he had spent the clearest of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were mattresses, blankets, tongs, clothes and glasses.
He tried to stay in motion, because sleeping or staying long during the day was contrary to the rules.
Manning also said that when he tried to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards didn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would awaken him so that they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint about Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
On Friday, too, the judge asked Manning about an allegation in his testimony on Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked one night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other detainees one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the appeal.
