The toughest trade in the world: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who work literally in hell.
This is the case with Antonio Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by wearing the sulfur of the Kawah Ijen volcano to the East of Indonesian Java Island.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfur gas emanating from the earth's bowels solidifies itself with the contact of the air.
After collecting large sulfur rocks, which weigh about 70 kilos in total, it installs them in two baskets in bamboo that it loads on its shoulders through the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters up to the top of the volcano which peaks at 2,386 meters above sea level, but the exhausted bearers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, to a tortoise, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents of euros for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once at the top, it spawns a path between tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and carrying painfully heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers up to the balance that a mining company has installed somewhat in front of them at 1,850 meters of altitude.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has operated the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents euros) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to 10,000 rupees (83 cents euros) to the petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in daily life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even serves to bleach sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (€3.8) for each trip," explains Anto, who generally travels three trips a day.
Each one takes 3 hours and ends up exhausted, but this allows it to win 18,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although this seems to be a misery for such a surhuman effort, it is the threefold of what he would gain in the fields.
"The income of minors is very high here, where the harvest of coffee is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the monthly average wage is two million rupees (167 euros)," the carrier who once worked as a mason on the island of Bali says.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (EUR 6.20 per day) and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, it is as undisputed as the sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they were Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to become Islam."
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, he spent three of his life challenging the danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulphur has already begun to make him pay the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and its eyes are irritated by toxic gases released by the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French" he promises in an English more than acceptable.
Poored by life, this young and intelligent friend could be a tourist guide, a waiter or a receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy wood mass with other carriers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulphur never ceases to wail at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto went down into the crater lighting up with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to the carriers who work on their behalf and are paid by weight.
