The Unasur Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) today ended in Peru without the release of the Lima Declaration, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe has tried several times to access the document signed at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency have initially reported that it would be disclosed after the summit was concluded, and then stated that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its content had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to summit information has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the soundless video of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulating among journalists was that given by press officers from some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, causing some discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Later, Peru's presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Arab South America Summit (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although this was requested at the press, it had also not broadcast the declaration also called Lima Declaration, as it had been previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In the two international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to establish secure transmission systems for all journalists, but have limited information to a maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court that sets out a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and stated that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear both parties' pleas in Lima's trial against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we bring today before this international court," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international tribunals," added President Piñera, handing President Humala a hand hand alongside the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was charged with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read out the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that 31 projects had been established between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of Unasur would put in place "important approaches to achieving the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve access to medicines, access to low-priced Internet throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (from Latin America) must not have a triumphal matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to anticipate a better future for our populations," concluded President Humala.
"We have decided to focus on a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, particularly in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian president in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were related to Peru and were on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aiming at a greater connection with Ecuador although it did not give more details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," which is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another topic addressed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on the following Saturday in Mexico City to discuss calmly the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
