"Hetin" Reyes basketball's balloon-trottor spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, he traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as big as that of Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage condemns him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, player of the national basketball team, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vacqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I wore several helmets in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the BSN, director general of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," recalls Reyes during a visit of Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball is my whole life."
Reyes doesn't exaggerate when he makes that statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with pictures and souvenirs that recall his unstandard route, bear witness to it.
Bayamon in the heart
Of all his memories, those he most affectionate are those who remind him of his passage as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-50s until 1982, after having spent 15 years as a co-manager or manager of the team.
"This was my best years, the ones I took the most advantage of because I had the chance to participate in eight Vacqueros championships from 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
This has been a great many years of satisfaction, including the five championships played from 1971 to 1975.
Then I retired at the 1981 championship, the year Jerome Mancy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead in the team," says Reyes.
