Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and climate warming.
This semester, when professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hammock there: the end of the "great discount" of the Maya calendar on December 21, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a fiscal gulf that some called "the Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where the Christian theorists of the end times thought would trigger the apocalypse.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," said Professor Charmé to his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey).
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and that we were saying it, it was a very good time.
And remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to teach on the "end of the world" this semester, which will be, in theory, the last of history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and climate warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could erupt.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
